I will not finish this certification even before i begin. Other certifications like W3 School are more user friendly. Please concider the way you are teaching. As other reviewers have said, the spoken content does not keep pace with the text on the slides which makes for an unsatisfactory experience. Assignment 2 (CSS) was wrongly coded and it took moderators a few days to look at comments from users and finally correct the scoring  algorithm.  The main problem with this course is though, by far, the breakneck pace with which the instructor (otherwise lovely in every way) is forced to go through the material, without stopping to explain the logic behind a coding convention or its practical applications. For CSS, not a single concrete example is given and the very first one such is encountered during the assignment ( no wonder the vast majorty of learnerns failed it, according to Coursera). There are far better courses on these topics  out there (UMich on this platform, all their courses are great, or the WEB3 Consortium's tutorials which are all very well taught- and free!). Sad to say, but I would not recommend this course to anyone - it needs vast improvements if it is to be of any value for someone who actually wants to learn these topics.

Os cursos do Coursera em geral possuem mais textos que vídeo, e este não foi diferente. Muitas legendas sem sincronia com o áudio, algumas legendas diferentes do áudio, atividades fora de ordem (te pergunta como foi o laboratório prático antes de você o faze-lo de fato). A maior parte das atividades práticas são avaliadas de forma automática com pouco ou nenhum feedback. Pode estar tudo certo, se tiver um espaço fora do lugar o resultado será errado e você que se vire pra achar a diferença. Cada problema que encontrei registrei no link "Relatar problema" em cada aula. Contudo, são cursos com milhares de alunos já matriculados. Isso significa que muitos outros já devem ter feito o mesmo mas provavelmente não há ninguém acompanhando, só vendendo curso.

​Extremely basic stuff. The "course" served more like an overview of what you need to learn than a real course. They covered very basic HTML, very basic CSS, some Bootstrap and skipped over JavaScript straight to React, where they only broadly defined components and the virtual DOM. The labs offer 100% handholding which I personally dislike, and are very laggy. The quizes were pretty straightforward and don't offer much learning value compared to a more practical approach like a project, which there was none. Conclusion: I got zero value out of it, but I can see it being somewhat useful for a complete beginner, I just think there are better already existing resources out there for that.  P​ros: good for a confused beginner to get an overview of the things he needs to learn to become a junior front-end web developer.C​ons: labs were way too easy, simplistic, rudimentary, laggy, and straight up offered the solutions instead of only providing the things you need to do, and only after to get the possibility to check what you've done. There was also no project, we didn't build anything. G​ave it 2 stars because I appreciated the attempt from Meta, but they need to work harder if they want to make a course / specialization worth more than the paper it's printed on. See you in the next one.

This comes from someone who has been coding in non-web environments for almost a decade, so the course was easy to knock out in a week. However, there are some obvious flaws in the teaching which added to the frustration, and minimized what I got from the course. The course content relies heavily on these well-produced videos, with an imperfect transcript. When you're going through a test or exercise, and need to reference code syntax, that means you have to scrub through the videos to find where they're showing an IDE on screen. That's incredibly frustrating as a learner, or it would be if not for the other issue here. Assignments don't evaluate your ability to understand HTML or CSS, they evaluate your ability to follow the step-by-step instructions given. In many of the labs the instructions are exceptionally detailed, telling me what to type in. A better evaluation would ask for what behavior they want on the page, and provide the ability to reference how to get there. Quite possibly a fine foundation for a brand new coder, but if you've got any familiarity at all with how computers work, you can probably get as good or better by referencing StackOverflow and the Boostrap docs.

Overall I have been satisfied with this course, and I intend to take the next course. I am starting from zero experience in anything tech related, and sometimes I feel like the course uses jargin or dives into concepts that I'm either supposed to already know, or catch on much more quickly. But, luckily (and possibly the point), I can review, re-read/watch content and google questions. I have many times extended my deadlines, and am learning at a slow pace, but that's the beauty of a casual online course like this. Also, I'm obviously no expert in the field, nor am I a teacher, but sometimes I feel that if this is to teach beginners, providing less info at one time could be beneficial. For example, I understand why they start off explaining how the internet works, but at the same time, its a lot of confusing and complicated information that won't really effect learning how to code. Sometimes less is more.

Meta's front-end developer course is a great option for freshers looking to start their career in web development. The course offers a comprehensive curriculum that covers all the necessary front-end technologies, such as HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, as well as advanced topics like React and responsive design.What makes this course stand out is its hands-on approach to learning. Students will work on real-world projects, building a portfolio of work that demonstrates their skills and knowledge. This practical experience is essential for freshers who need to showcase their abilities to potential employers.The course also offers career support, helping students to develop their resumes, prepare for interviews, and connect with potential employers. The instructors are experienced professionals in the industry, and they provide valuable guidance and mentorship throughout the course.Overall, Meta's front-end developer course is an excellent choice for freshers who want to learn web development and start a career in the industry. It provides a strong foundation of skills and knowledge, practical experience, and career support to help students achieve their goals.

I​nroduction to Front-End Development takes you an information ride that will lead you to the destination of being able to craete a fully workable web site. The tutorial videos is what really makes this an enjoyable experience as you will not only just see, but actually get a "hands on" expierence by engaging in these labs as they call them. From time to time, you are quizzed with a question which acts as a " if you are paying attention to the information that is parted to you type question". And between each section, there is a graded quiz in which you must pass with 80% of greater, else your journey crawls to a complate standstill. Fail 3 times and you wont be able to retake a test until at least eight hours has passed. But by the time you have finished the intro, you will( or should) truly have a solid foundation of what html is, css and how to work with with the bootstrap library. I say the last part provided that you are PAYING ATTENTION and retaining a working memory of what is being taught to you. So you if you just learn and know what is is being taught, then you will fall short if you can't understand what is being taught to you. And that's with anything in life. In closing, if are really wanting to know, learn and understand Front-End Development then this course is for you. You will be taught my Meta professionals and they have done a great job in putting together a solid learning structure for someone that want to know what Front End Development is all about.

I have come a long way in one week, supplemented my knowledge and learned many new techniques, I love this course, it opened up a big world of web development for me, and this is just the beginning of my journey. I did a lot of documentation, I’ve been passing many times all assignments on 100% each, now I read some books that Meta recommended for me, and I see the result of my efforts. I want to dive deep into development and come up with new methods and approaches to be more experienced and dynamic in the future, I used many forums and websites, searched and tried, communicated and helped the guys on Coursera, I'm translating the course from English to Russian, so that in the future other people can also study here without language difficulties.I believe that if you make an effort, be persistent, do not stop, believe in yourself and value time, then you can move mountains. You can achieve what you want by being brave and ready to face difficulties and overcome them. My goal is much more than just being a frontend, my goal is to become a multi-faceted developer who can help many people with different technical needs.
